The Akwa Ibom State government has translated and unveiled into local dialects the “Wetin Udom Don Do” magazine, one of its publications The translated magazine, which are now in Ibibio, Annang and Oro versions filled with both textual and pictorial materials focusing on the activities, programmes and policies of Governor Udom Emmanuel’s administration, as well as the unique marketing potentials of Akwa Ibom state. Performing the unveiling ceremony for the vernacular versions of the publication, on Monday in the Conference room of the Ministry, the Commissioner for Information and Strategy, Comrade Ini Ememobong said that the innovation was geared at gaining wider reach of the people in the local communities through their local dialects. “The Ministry will not rest on its oars until it completely discharges its mandate of feeding the public with government policies, programmes and activities,” Ememobong said. He disclosed that the Ministry would fight all barriers that would hinder it from carrying out its mandate of Public enlightenment and getting citizens feedback to government for an effective citizens participation in governance. Ememobong who was addressing Information officers serving in the 31 local government areas of the state, hinted that the translation, of the publication in the three major dialects of the people of the state was borne out of the need to ensure that Akwa Ibom citizens in rural areas have access to Governor Udom Emmanuel’s programmes and activities without any hindrance. He said that the state government would continue to be transparent and accessible to the public while also evolving feedback mechanism through the ministry for enhanced public participation in government processes. Speaking at the ceremony the Permanent Secretary, Akparawa James Edet tasked the staff to disseminate and circulate the publications as good ambassadors of the government to every nook and cranny of the state.